 1330–28 mei 1381","1325–1383":"1325–1383","1330–1381":"1330–1381","1320–1384":"1320–1384","1343–1395":"1343–1395","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1305–1384":"1305–1384","28 May 1381":"28 mei 1381","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","before 10 August 1353":"vóór 10 augustus 1353","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","24 March 1330":"24 maart 1330","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","shortly before 2 November 1335":"vóór 2 november 1335","May 1381":"mei 1381","Danby, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Guisborough, Yorkshire, England":"Guisborough, Yorkshire, England","Scampston, Yorkshire, England":"Scampston, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"24 March 1330–28 May 1381":"24 March 1330–28 May 1381","1325–1383":"1325–1383","1330–1381":"1330–1381","1320–1384":"1320–1384","1343–1395":"1343–1395","1300–1335":"1300–1335","1305–1384":"1305–1384","28 May 1381":"28 May 1381","1330":"1330","1395":"1395","1384":"1384","1383":"1383","1381":"1381","before 10 August 1353":"before 10 August 1353","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","24 March 1330":"24 March 1330","1335":"1335","1300":"1300","1343":"1343","1453":"1453","1320":"1320","shortly before 2 November 1335":"before 2 November 1335","May 1381":"May 1381","Danby, East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Guisborough, Yorkshire, England":"Guisborough, Yorkshire, England","Scampston, Yorkshire, England":"Scampston, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Latimer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a Latinist, a clerk who wrote documents in Latin, from Anglo-Norman French <i>latinier</i>, <i>latim(m)ier</i>. Latin was more or less the universal language of official documents in the Middle Ages, displaced only gradually by the vernacular – in England, by Anglo-Norman French at first, and eventually by English."],"variants":[{"name":"Latner","meanings":["English: occupational name for a worker in or maker of latten or brass, from Middle English <i>latoun</i> ‘brass’ (Old French <i>laton</i>). This name may sometimes have been confused with   Latimer  .","Altered form of German   Lattner   or   Lettner  ."]},{"name":"Lattimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Latimore","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattimer","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  ."]},{"name":"Lattner","meanings":["English: variant of   Latimer  .","German: occupational name for a carpenter who prepared or used laths or slats, from Middle High German <i>latte</i> ‘slat, lath’ + <i>-n</i> (plural suffix) + the agent suffix <i>-er</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":6,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Latimer 4th Baron was born on 24 March 1330, in Scampston, Yorkshire, England, his father, William Latimer 3rd Baron Latimer of Corby, was 31 and his mother, 